# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ecommerce-platform
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] A **digital wallet**, also known as an **e-wallet** or **mobile wallet**, is an electronic device, online service, or software program that allows one party to make electronic transactions with another party by exchanging digital currency units for goods and services.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] This can include purchasing items either online or at the point of sale in a brick-and-mortar store, either using a smartphone or other mobile device to make a mobile payment or (for online buying only) using a laptop or other personal computer.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Money can be deposited in the digital wallet prior to any such transactions; alternatively, an individual's bank account can be linked to the digital wallet.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Users may also have their driver's license, health card, loyalty card(s) and other ID documents stored within the wallet.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] The credentials can be passed to a merchant's terminal wirelessly via near field communication (NFC).
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Increasingly, digital wallets are being made not just for basic financial transactions but to also authenticate the holder's credentials.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] For example, a digital wallet could verify the age of the buyer to the store while purchasing alcohol.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] The system has already gained popularity in Japan, where digital wallets are known as "wallet mobiles".
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] In addition, a few US states have adapted digital driver's licenses and state IDs to be added to digital wallet instead of the physical card and it can be used at selected Transportation Security Administration checkpoints at airports, banking or enterprise.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] As of January 2025 the UK government is launching a GOV.UK wallet which will allow users to hold digital versions of various government documents within a mobile phone.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] A cryptocurrency wallet is a digital wallet where private keys are stored for cryptocurrencies like bitcoin.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] A digital wallet has both a software and information component.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Secure and fair electronic payment systems are an important issue.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] The software provides security and encryption for the personal information and for the actual transaction.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Typically, digital wallets are stored on the client side and are easily self-maintained and fully compatible with most e-commerce websites.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] A server-side digital wallet, also known as a thin wallet, is one that an organization creates for and about its members and maintains on its servers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Server-side digital wallets are gaining popularity among major retailers due to the security, efficiency, and added utility it provides to the end-user, which increases their satisfaction of their overall purchase.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] The information component is basically a database of user-input information.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] This information consists of a user's shipping address, billing address, payment methods (including credit card numbers, expiry dates, and security numbers), and other information.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Digital wallets are composed of both digital wallet devices and digital wallet systems.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] There are dedicated digital wallet devices such as the biometric wallet by Dunhill, a physical device that holds cash and cards along with a Bluetooth mobile connection.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Presently there are further explorations for smartphones with NFC digital wallet capabilities, such as smartphones utilizing Google's Android and Apple's iOS operating systems to power wallets such as Google Wallet and Apple Pay.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Digital wallet systems enable the widespread use of digital wallet transactions among various retail vendors in the form of mobile payments systems and digital wallet applications.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] The M-PESA mobile payments system and microfinancing service has widespread use in Kenya and Tanzania, while the MasterCard PayPass application has been adopted by a number of vendors in the U.S. and worldwide.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Digital wallets are being used more frequently among Asian countries as well.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] One in every five consumers in Asia are now using a digital wallet, representing a twofold increase from two years ago.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] A MasterCard mobile shopping survey among 8500 adults, aged 18–64 across 14 markets, showed that 45% of users in China, 36.7% of users in India and 23.3% of users in Singapore are the biggest adopters of digital wallets.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] The survey was conducted between October and December 2015.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Further analysis showed that 48.5% of consumers in these regions made purchases using smartphones.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Indian consumers are leading the way with 76.4% using a smartphone to make a purchase, which is a drastic increase of 29.3% from the previous year.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] This has inspired companies like Reliance and Amazon India to come out with their own digital wallet.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Flipkart has already introduced its own digital wallet.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] A 2025 systematic review found that digital wallet and mobile payment technologies play a significant role in expanding financial inclusion by lowering access barriers and improving the availability of financial services for underserved populations.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Consumers are not required to fill out order forms on each site when they purchase an item because the information has already been stored and is automatically updated and entered into the order fields across merchant sites when using a digital wallet.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Consumers also benefit when using digital wallets because their information is encrypted or protected by a private software code; merchants benefit by receiving a combination of protection against fraud, faster receipt of payment, decreased transaction costs, and decreased theft loss.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Digital wallets are available to consumers free of charge, and they're fairly easy to obtain.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] For example, when a consumer makes a purchase at a merchant site that's set up to handle server-side digital wallets, they type their name, payment and shipping information into the merchant's own form.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] At the end of the purchase, the consumer is asked to sign up for a wallet of their choice by entering a user name and password for future purchases.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Users can also acquire wallets at a wallet vendor's site.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] Most, if not all digital wallets offer advanced security features e.g. biometric authentication and encryption, this protects the financial information of the users thus preventing fraud.
[src:ecommerce-platform/digital-wallet] With the acquisition of iDEAL, European Payments Initiative Company has announced that it will create an all European digital wallet.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The term was coined and first employed by Robert Jacobson, Principal Consultant to the California State Assembly's Utilities & Commerce Committee, in the title and text of California's Electronic Commerce Act, carried by the late Committee Chairwoman Gwen Moore (D-L.A.) and enacted in 1984.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] E-commerce typically uses the web for at least a part of a transaction's life cycle although it may also use other technologies such as e-mail.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Typical e-commerce transactions include the purchase of products (such as books from Amazon) or services (such as music downloads in the form of digital distribution such as the iTunes Store).
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] There are three areas of e-commerce: online retailing, electronic markets, and online auctions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] E-commerce is supported by electronic business.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The existence value of e-commerce is to allow consumers to shop online and pay online through the Internet, saving the time and space of customers and enterprises, greatly improving transaction efficiency, especially for busy office workers, and also saving a lot of valuable time.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Contemporary electronic commerce can be classified into two categories.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The first category is business based on types of goods sold (involves everything from ordering "digital" content for immediate online consumption, to ordering conventional goods and services, to "meta" services to facilitate other types of electronic commerce).
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The second category is based on the nature of the participant (B2B, B2C, C2B and C2C).
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] On the institutional level, big corporations and financial institutions use the internet to exchange financial data to facilitate domestic and international business.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Data integrity and security are pressing issues for electronic commerce.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Aside from traditional e-commerce, the terms m-Commerce (mobile commerce) as well (around 2013) t-Commerce have also been used.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In the United States, California's Electronic Commerce Act (1984), enacted by the Legislature, the more recent California Privacy Rights Act (2020), enacted through a popular election proposition and to control specifically how electronic commerce may be conducted in California.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In the US in its entirety, electronic commerce activities are regulated more broadly by the Federal Trade Commission (FTC).
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] These activities include the use of commercial e-mails, online advertising and consumer privacy.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The CAN-SPAM Act of 2003 establishes national standards for direct marketing over e-mail.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The Federal Trade Commission Act regulates all forms of advertising, including online advertising, and states that advertising must be truthful and non-deceptive.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Using its authority under Section 5 of the FTC Act, which prohibits unfair or deceptive practices, the FTC has brought a number of cases to enforce the promises in corporate privacy statements, including promises about the security of consumers' personal information.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] As a result, any corporate privacy policy related to e-commerce activity may be subject to enforcement by the FTC.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The Ryan Haight Online Pharmacy Consumer Protection Act of 2008, which came into law in 2008, amends the Controlled Substances Act to address online pharmacies.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Conflict of laws in cyberspace is a major hurdle for harmonization of legal framework for e-commerce around the world.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In order to give a uniformity to e-commerce law around the world, many countries adopted the UNCITRAL Model Law on Electronic Commerce (1996).
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] There is also **Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation**.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] APEC was established in 1989 with the vision of achieving stability, security and prosperity for the region through free and open trade and investment.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] APEC has an Electronic Commerce Steering Group as well as working on common privacy regulations throughout the APEC region.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In **Australia**, trade is covered under Australian Treasury Guidelines for electronic commerce and the Australian Competition & Consumer Commission regulates and offers advice on how to deal with businesses online, and offers specific advice on what happens if things go wrong.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In **the United Kingdom**, the Financial Services Authority (FSA) was formerly the regulating authority for most aspects of the EU's Payment Services Directive (PSD), until its replacement in 2013 by the Prudential Regulation Authority and the Financial Conduct Authority.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The UK implemented the PSD through the Payment Services Regulations 2009 (PSRs), which came into effect on 1 November 2009.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The PSR affects firms providing payment services and their customers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] These firms include banks, non-bank credit card issuers and non-bank merchant acquirers, e-money issuers, etc.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The PSRs created a new class of regulated firms known as payment institutions (PIs), who are subject to prudential requirements.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Article 87 of the PSD required the European Commission to report on the implementation and impact of the PSD by 1 November 2012.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In **India**, the Information Technology Act 2000 governs the basic applicability of e-commerce.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] On the same day, the Administrative Measures on Internet Information Services were released, the first administrative regulations to address profit-generating activities conducted through the Internet, and lay the foundation for future regulations governing e-commerce in China.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] On 28 August 2004, the eleventh session of the tenth NPC Standing Committee adopted an Electronic Signature Law, which regulates data message, electronic signature authentication and legal liability issues.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] It is considered the first law in China's e-commerce legislation.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] It was a milestone in the course of improving China's electronic commerce legislation, and also marks the entering of China's rapid development stage for electronic commerce legislation.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] E-commerce has become an important tool for small and large businesses worldwide, not only to sell to customers, but also to engage them.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Cross-border e-Commerce is also an essential field for e-Commerce businesses.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] It has responded to the trend of globalization.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] It shows that numerous firms have opened up new businesses, expanded new markets, and overcome trade barriers; more and more enterprises have started exploring the cross-border cooperation field.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In addition, compared with traditional cross-border trade, the information on cross-border e-commerce is more concealed.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In the era of globalization, cross-border e-commerce for inter-firm companies means the activities, interactions, or social relations of two or more e-commerce enterprises.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] However, the success of cross-border e-commerce promotes the development of small and medium-sized firms, and it has finally become a new transaction mode.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] It has helped the companies solve financial problems and realize the reasonable allocation of resources field.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] SMEs (small and medium enterprises) can also precisely match the demand and supply in the market, having the industrial chain majorization and creating more revenues for companies.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In 2012, e-commerce sales topped $1 trillion for the first time in history.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Mobile devices are playing an increasing role in the mix of e-commerce, this is also commonly called mobile commerce, or m-commerce.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In 2014, one estimate saw purchases made on mobile devices making up 25% of the market by 2017.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] For traditional businesses, one research stated that information technology and cross-border e-commerce is a good opportunity for the rapid development and growth of enterprises.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Many companies have invested an enormous volume of investment in mobile applications.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The DeLone and McLean Model stated that three perspectives contribute to a successful e-business: information system quality, service quality and users' satisfaction.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Modern 3D graphics technologies, such as Facebook 3D Posts, are considered by some social media marketers and advertisers as a preferable way to promote consumer goods than static photos, and some brands like Sony are already paving the way for augmented reality commerce.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Wayfair now lets you inspect a 3D version of its furniture in a home setting before buying.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Among emerging economies, China's e-commerce presence continued to expand every year.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] With 668 million Internet users as of 2014, China's online shopping sales reached $253 billion in the first half of 2015, accounting for 10% of total Chinese consumer retail sales in that period.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The Chinese retailers have been able to help consumers feel more comfortable shopping online. e-commerce transactions between China and other countries increased 32% to 2.3 trillion yuan ($375.8 billion) in 2012 and accounted for 9.6% of China's total international trade.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In 2013, Alibaba had an e-commerce market share of 80% in China.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In 2014, Alibaba still dominated the B2B marketplace in China with a market share of 44.82%, followed by several other companies including Made-in-China.com at 3.21%, and GlobalSources.com at 2.98%, with the total transaction value of China's B2B market exceeding 4.5 billion yuan.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In 2012, Alibaba Group delisted Alibaba.com from the Hong Kong stock exchange after acquiring full control.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In 2014, it was privately held again following a $2.5 billion buyback.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The company's NYSE debut under the stock ticker BABA made headlines for being, at that time, the biggest IPO in U.S. history.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Alibaba's International Digital Commerce Group (AIDC), which includes Alibaba.com's B2B operations, reported 22% year-over-year revenue growth in the quarter ending March 31, 2025 (Q4 FY2025).
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] China was also the largest e-commerce market in the world by value of sales, with an estimated US$899 billion in 2016.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] It accounted for 42.4% of worldwide retail e-commerce in that year, the most of any country.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Research shows that Chinese consumer motivations are different enough from Western audiences to require unique e-commerce app designs instead of simply porting Western apps into the Chinese market.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The expansion of e-commerce in China has resulted in the development of Taobao villages, clusters of e-commerce businesses operating in rural areas.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Because Taobao villages have increased the incomes or rural people and entrepreneurship in rural China, Taobao villages have become a component of rural revitalization strategies.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In 2015, the State Council promoted the Internet Plus initiative, a five-year plan to integrate traditional manufacturing and service industries with big data, cloud computing, and Internet of things technology.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The State Council provided support for Internet Plus through policy support in area including cross-border e-commerce and rural e-commerce.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In 2019, the city of Hangzhou established a pilot program artificial intelligence-based Internet Court to adjudicate disputes related to e-commerce and internet-related intellectual property claims.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In 2010, the United Kingdom had the highest per capita e-commerce spending in the world.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] As of 2013, the Czech Republic was the European country where e-commerce delivers the biggest contribution to the enterprises' total revenue.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Almost a quarter (24%) of the country's total turnover is generated via the online channel.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The rate of growth of the number of internet users in the Arab countries has been rapid – 13.1% in 2015.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] A significant portion of the e-commerce market in the Middle East comprises people in the 30–34 year age group.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Egypt has the largest number of internet users in the region, followed by Saudi Arabia and Morocco; these constitute 3/4th of the region's share.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Yet, internet penetration is low: 35% in Egypt and 65% in Saudi Arabia.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The Gulf Cooperation Council countries have a rapidly growing market and are characterized by a population that becomes wealthier (Yuldashev).
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] As such, retailers have launched Arabic-language websites as a means to target this population.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Secondly, there are predictions of increased mobile purchases and an expanding internet audience (Yuldashev).
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The growth and development of the two aspects make the GCC countries become larger players in the electronic commerce market with time progress.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Specifically, research shows that the e-commerce market was expected to grow to over $20 billion by 2020 among these GCC countries (Yuldashev).
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The e-commerce market has also gained much popularity among western countries, and in particular Europe and the U.S.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] These countries have been highly characterized by consumer-packaged goods (CPG) (Geisler, 34).
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] However, trends show that there are future signs of a reverse.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Similar to the GCC countries, there has been increased purchase of goods and services in online channels rather than offline channels.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Activist investors are trying hard to consolidate and slash their overall cost and the governments in western countries continue to impose more regulation on CPG manufacturers (Geisler, 36).
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In these senses, CPG investors are being forced to adapt to e-commerce as it is effective as well as a means for them to thrive.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The future trends in the GCC countries will be similar to that of the western countries.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Despite the forces that push business to adapt e-commerce as a means to sell goods and products, the manner in which customers make purchases is similar in countries from these two regions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] For instance, there has been an increased usage of smartphones which comes in conjunction with an increase in the overall internet audience from the regions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Yuldashev writes that consumers are scaling up to more modern technology that allows for mobile marketing.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] However, the percentage of smartphone and internet users who make online purchases is expected to vary in the first few years.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] It will be independent on the willingness of the people to adopt this new trend (The Statistics Portal).
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] For example, UAE has the greatest smartphone penetration of 73.8 per cent and has 91.9 per cent of its population has access to the internet.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] On the other hand, smartphone penetration in Europe has been reported to be at 64.7 per cent (The Statistics Portal).
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Regardless, the disparity in percentage between these regions is expected to level out in future because e-commerce technology is expected to grow to allow for more users.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The e-commerce business within these two regions will result in competition.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Government bodies at the country level will enhance their measures and strategies to ensure sustainability and consumer protection (Krings, et al.).
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] These increased measures will raise the environmental and social standards in the countries, factors that will determine the success of the e-commerce market in these countries.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] For example, an adoption of tough sanctions will make it difficult for companies to enter the e-commerce market while lenient sanctions will allow ease of companies.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] As such, the future trends between GCC countries and the Western countries will be independent of these sanctions (Krings, et al.).
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] These countries need to make rational conclusions in coming up with effective sanctions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] India had an Internet user base of about 460 million as of December 2017.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Despite being the third largest user base in the world, the penetration of the Internet is low compared to markets like the United States, United Kingdom or France but is growing at a much faster rate, adding around six million new entrants every month.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In India, cash on delivery is the most preferred payment method, accumulating 75% of the e-retail activities.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The India retail market was expected to rise from 2.5% in 2016 to 5% in 2020.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In 2013, Brazil's e-commerce was growing quickly with retail e-commerce sales expected to grow at a double-digit pace through 2014.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] By 2016, eMarketer expected retail e-commerce sales in Brazil to reach $17.3 billion.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Logistics in e-commerce mainly concerns fulfillment.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Online markets and retailers have to find the best possible way to fill orders and deliver products.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Small companies usually control their own logistic operation because they do not have the ability to hire an outside company.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Most large companies hire a fulfillment service that takes care of a company's logistic needs.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The optimization of logistics processes that contains long-term investment in an efficient storage infrastructure system and adoption of inventory management strategies is crucial to prioritize customer satisfaction throughout the entire process, from order placement to final delivery.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] E-commerce markets grew at noticeable rates.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The online market was expected to grow by 56% in 2015–2020.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In 2017, retail e-commerce sales worldwide amounted to 2.3 trillion US dollars and e-retail revenues were projected to grow to 4.891 trillion US dollars in 2021.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Traditional markets were only expected 2% growth during the same time.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Brick and mortar retailers are struggling because of online retailer's ability to offer lower prices and higher efficiency.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Many larger retailers are able to maintain a presence offline and online by linking physical and online offerings.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] E-commerce allows customers to overcome geographical barriers and to purchase products anytime and from anywhere.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Online and traditional markets have different strategies.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Traditional retailers offer fewer assortment of products because of shelf space where.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Online retailers often hold no inventory but send customer orders directly to the manufacturer.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Dropshipping is a means of shipping goods from a manufacturer or wholesaler directly to a customer instead of to a retailer.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] This process results in the vendor not holding any stock but serving as an intermediary between the buyer and the third-party supplier.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The dropshipping market is expected to reach $1.51 Tn by 2032, according to a Global Market Insights report, which studied the main dropshipping markets, including Alibaba.com, Chinabrands.com, Doba, Printful, Salehoo, Shopify, and Spocket.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The pricing strategies are also different for traditional and online retailers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Traditional retailers base their prices on store traffic and the cost to keep inventory.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Online retailers base prices on the speed of delivery.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] E-commerce merchants may operate fully online, or online along with a brick and mortar store.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Online marketers can offer lower prices, greater product selection, and high efficiency rates.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Many customers prefer online markets if the products can be delivered quickly at relatively low price.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] However, online retailers cannot offer the physical experience that traditional retailers can.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] It can be difficult to judge the quality of a product without the physical experience, which may cause customers to experience product or seller uncertainty.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Another issue regarding the online market is concerns about the security of online transactions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Many customers remain loyal to well-known retailers because of this issue.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Security is a primary problem for e-commerce in developed and developing countries.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] E-commerce security is protecting businesses' websites and customers from unauthorized access, use, alteration, or destruction.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Threats include: malicious codes, unwanted programs (ad ware, spyware), phishing, hacking, and cyber vandalism.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Tools to avert these threats include firewalls, encryption software, digital certificates, and passwords.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] For a long time, companies had been troubled by the gap between the benefits which supply chain technology has and the solutions to deliver those benefits.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] However, the emergence of e-commerce has provided a more practical and effective way of delivering the benefits of the new supply chain technologies.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] E-commerce has the capability to integrate all inter-company and intra-company functions, meaning that the three flows (physical flow, financial flow and information flow) of the supply chain could be also affected by e-commerce.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The affections on physical flows improved the way of product and inventory movement level for companies.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] For the information flows, e-commerce optimized the capacity of information processing than companies used to have, and for the financial flows, e-commerce allows companies to have more efficient payment and settlement solutions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Yet these new capabilities are still not fully exploited.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Thirdly, technology companies would keep investing on new e-commerce software solutions as they are expecting investment return.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Fourthly, e-commerce would help to solve many aspects of issues that companies may feel difficult to cope with, such as political barriers or cross-country changes.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Finally, e-commerce provides companies a more efficient and effective way to collaborate with each other within the supply chain.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] E-commerce helps create new job opportunities due to information related services, software app and digital products.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The areas with the greatest predicted job-loss are retail, postal, and travel agencies.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The development of e-commerce will create jobs that require highly skilled workers to manage large amounts of information, customer demands, and production processes.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In contrast, people with poor technical skills cannot enjoy the wages welfare.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] On the other hand, because e-commerce requires sufficient stocks that could be delivered to customers in time, the warehouse becomes an important element.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Warehouse needs more staff to manage, supervise and organize, thus the condition of warehouse environment will be concerned by employees.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] E-commerce brings convenience for customers as they do not have to leave home and only need to browse websites online, especially for buying products which are not sold in nearby shops.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] It could help customers buy a wider range of products and save customers' time.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Consumers also gain power through online shopping.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] They are able to research products and compare prices among retailers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Thanks to the practice of user-generated ratings and reviews from companies like Bazaarvoice, Trustpilot, and Yelp, customers can also see what other people think of a product, and decide before buying if they want to spend money on it.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Also, online shopping often provides sales promotion or discounts code, thus it is more price effective for customers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Moreover, e-commerce provides products' detailed information; even the in-store staff cannot offer such detailed explanation.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Customers can also review and track the order history online.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] E-commerce technologies cut transaction costs by allowing both manufactures and consumers to skip through the intermediaries.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] This is achieved through by extending the search area best price deals and by group purchase.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The success of e-commerce in urban and regional levels depend on how the local firms and consumers have adopted to e-commerce.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] However, e-commerce lacks human interaction for customers, especially who prefer face-to-face connection.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Customers are also concerned with the security of online transactions and tend to remain loyal to well-known retailers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In recent years, clothing retailers such as Tommy Hilfiger have started adding Virtual Fit platforms to their e-commerce sites to reduce the risk of customers buying the wrong sized clothes, although these vary greatly in their fit for purpose.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] When the customer regret the purchase of a product, it involves returning goods and refunding process.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] This process is inconvenient as customers need to pack and post the goods.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] If the products are expensive, large or fragile, it refers to safety issues.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In 2018, E-commerce generated 1.3 million short tons (1.2 megatonnes) of container cardboard in North America, an increase from 1.1 million (1.00)) in 2017.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Only 35 percent of North American cardboard manufacturing capacity was from recycled content.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The recycling rate in Europe was 80 percent and Asia was 93 percent.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Amazon, the largest user of boxes, had a strategy to cut back on packing material and reduced packaging material used by 19 percent by weight since 2016.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Amazon is requiring retailers to manufacture their product packaging in a way that does not require additional shipping packaging.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Amazon also has an 85-person team researching ways to reduce and improve their packaging and shipping materials.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Accelerated movement of packages around the world includes accelerated movement of living things, such as invasive species.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Weeds, pests, and diseases all sometimes travel in packages of seeds.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Some of these packages are part of brushing manipulation of e-commerce reviews.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Many companies have turned to sales promotions and increased digital efforts to lure shoppers while shutting down brick-and-mortar locations.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] The trend has forced some traditional retailers to shutter its brick and mortar operations.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] In March 2020, global retail website traffic hit 14.3 billion visits signifying an unprecedented growth of e-commerce during the lockdown of 2020.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Later studies show that online sales increased by 25% and online grocery shopping increased by over 100% during the crisis in the United States.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Meanwhile, as many as 29% of surveyed shoppers state that they will never go back to shopping in person again; in the UK, 43% of consumers state that they expect to keep on shopping the same way even after the lockdown is over.
[src:ecommerce-platform/e-commerce] Retail sales of e-commerce shows that COVID-19 has a significant impact on e-commerce and its sales were expected to reach $6.5 trillion by 2023.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Online stores that evoke the physical analogy of buying products or services at a regular "brick-and-mortar" retailer or shopping center follow a process called business-to-consumer (B2C) online shopping.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] When an online store is set up to enable businesses to buy from another business, the process is instead called business-to-business (B2B) online shopping.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] A typical online store enables the customer to browse the firm's range of products and services, view photos or images of the products, along with information about the product specifications, features and prices.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Unlike physical stores which may close at night, online shopping portals are always available to customers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Online stores usually enable shoppers to use "search" features to find specific models, brands or items.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Online customers must have access to the Internet and a valid method of payment in order to complete a transaction, such as a credit card, an Interac-enabled debit card, or a service such as PayPal.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] For physical products (e.g., paperback books or clothes), the e-tailer ships the products to the customer; for digital products, such as digital audio files of songs or software, the e-tailer usually sends the file to the customer over the Internet.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The largest of these online retailing corporations are Alibaba, Amazon.com, and eBay.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Alternative names for the activity are "e-commerce", a shortened form of "electronic commerce" or "e-shopping", a shortened form of "electronic shopping".
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] An online store may also be called an e-web-store, e-shop, e-store, Internet shop, web-shop, web-store, online store, online storefront and virtual store.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Mobile commerce (or m-commerce) describes purchasing from an online retailer's mobile device-optimized website or software application ("app").
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] These websites or apps are designed to enable customers to browse through a companies' products and services on tablet computers and smartphones.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] One of the earliest forms of trade conducted online was IBM's online transaction processing (OLTP) developed in the 1960s, which allowed the processing of financial transactions in real-time.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The computerized ticket reservation system developed for American Airlines called Semi-Automatic Business Research Environment (SABRE) was one of its applications.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] There, computer terminals located in different travel agencies were linked to a large IBM mainframe computer, which processed transactions simultaneously and coordinated them so that all travel agents had access to the same information at the same time.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] At some point between 1971 and 1972, students at Stanford and MIT used the internet precursor ARPANET to make a deal to exchange marijuana, but the interaction does not qualify as e-commerce because no money was transferred online.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The landscape of online shopping as we know it today took shape with the rise of the Internet.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Initially serving as a mere advertising platform, the Internet transitioned swiftly into a dynamic space for actual online transactions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] This transformation was fueled by the development of interactive web pages and secure transmission protocols, marking a pivotal moment in 1994 with the first online sales of Sting's album, *Ten Summoner's Tales*.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] This milestone event set the stage for the diversification of online retail, with early adopters such as wine, chocolates, and flowers paving the way.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] These products became pioneers in the e-commerce realm, capturing the attention of a growing audience.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Researchers identified a crucial factor for internet success – the suitability of products for online transactions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Generic items that didn't necessitate physical interaction gained traction, propelling the online shopping trend forward.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In its nascent stages, online shopping faced a limited audience.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The early adopters were predominantly affluent males aged 30 and above.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] However, this demographic landscape underwent significant changes over time, and the online shopping sphere became more inclusive.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Over the years, the United Kingdom has witnessed a substantial shift in consumer behavior, with online shopping accounting for a noteworthy percentage of retail transactions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The extent of this influence varies depending on the product category, highlighting the diverse ways in which consumers engage with online platforms.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] As the revenues from online sales continued to grow significantly researchers identified different types of online shoppers, Rohm & Swaninathan identified four categories and named them "*convenience shoppers, variety seekers, balanced buyers, and store-oriented shoppers*".
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] They focused on shopping motivations and found that the variety of products available and the perceived convenience of the buying online experience were significant motivating factors.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] This was different for offline shoppers, who were more motivated by time saving and recreational motives.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] English entrepreneur Michael Aldrich was a pioneer of online shopping in 1979.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] His system connected a modified domestic TV to a real-time transaction processing computer via a domestic telephone line.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] His definition of the new mass communications medium as 'participative' [interactive, many-to-many] was fundamentally different from the traditional definitions of mass communication and mass media and a precursor to the social networking on the Internet 25 years later.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In March 1980 he launched Redifon's Office Revolution, which allowed consumers, customers, agents, distributors, suppliers and service companies to be connected online to the corporate systems and allow business transactions to be completed electronically in real-time.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] During the 1980s he designed, manufactured, sold, installed, maintained and supported many online shopping systems, using videotex technology.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] These systems which also provided voice response and handprint processing pre-date the Internet and the World Wide Web, the IBM PC, and Microsoft MS-DOS, and were installed mainly in the UK by large corporations.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The first World Wide Web server and browser, created by Tim Berners-Lee in 1989, opened for commercial use in 1991.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Thereafter, subsequent technological innovations emerged in 1994: online banking, the opening of an online pizza shop by Pizza Hut, Netscape's SSL v2 encryption standard for secure data transfer, and Intershop's first online shopping system.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The first secure retail transaction over the Web was either by NetMarket or Internet Shopping Network in 1994.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Immediately after, Amazon.com launched its online shopping site in 1995 and eBay was also introduced in 1995.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Alibaba's sites Taobao and Tmall were launched in 2003 and 2008, respectively.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Retailers are increasingly selling goods and services prior to availability through "pretail" for testing, building, and managing demand.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Statistics show that in 2012, Asia-Pacific increased their international sales over 30% giving them over $433 billion in revenue.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] That is a $69 billion difference between the U.S. revenue of $364.66 billion.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] It is estimated that Asia-Pacific will increase by another 30% in the year 2013 putting them ahead by more than one-third of all global e-commerce sales.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The largest online shopping day in the world is Singles Day, with sales just in Alibaba's sites at US$9.3 billion in 2014.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In 2018, 9.8% of all retail sales in the United States were made online.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In 2019, that figure was 2.8% in Canada.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In the United Kingdom, online sales peaked at 37.8% of all retail sales in January 2021, and were at 26.3% in January 2024.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Online customers must have access to the Internet and a valid method of payment in order to complete a transaction.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Generally, higher levels of education and personal income correspond to more favorable perceptions of shopping online.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Increased exposure to technology also increases the probability of developing favorable attitudes towards new shopping channels.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In addition, age is also a significant factor that affects online shopping.Culture can have a big effect on how shoppers trust reviews and make important decisions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] People in different countries can respond differently to online information than someone from their own country.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] On top of that, after the pandemic, it seems that more people are relying on online websites for things they used to buy in person at the store.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] People feel that privacy and security factors have an even more significant impact on attitudes toward online shopping than product factors.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Shoppers of different age groups have different perceptions of the risk factors of online shopping.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The marketing around the digital environment, customer's buying behaviour may not be influenced and controlled by the brand and firm, when they make a buying decision that might concern the interactions with search engine, recommendations, online reviews and other information.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In modern shopping environments, people are more likely to use their mobile phones, computers, tablets and other digital devices to gather information.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] When people shop online, how risky they feel when purchasing an item plays a big role.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Websites that offer secure payment options and good delivery systems make shoppers feel safer and more open to making a purchase.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Plus, the way reviews are presented with like the design of the site, layout, and pictures, will also really influence their decisions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In an online shopping environment, interactive decision may have an influence on aid customer decision making, through online product reviews and user-generated content, typically provided through software from companies like Bazaarvoice and Trustpilot, or via social media.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] This content, which can include text or video-based reviews, customer photos, and feedback, is often displayed alongside products being sold on websites like Amazon, Target, and most other digital storefronts.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Subsequently, risk and trust would also are two important factors affecting people's' behavior in digital environments.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Customers consider to switch between e-channels, because they are mainly influence by the comparison with offline shopping, involving growth of security, financial and performance-risks In other words, a customer shopping online that they may receive more risk than people shopping in stores.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] There are three factors may influence people to do the buying decision, firstly, people cannot examine whether the product satisfy their needs and wants before they receive it.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Secondly, customer may concern at after-sale services.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Finally, customer may afraid that they cannot fully understand the language used in e-sales.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Based on those factors customer perceive risk may as a significantly reason influence the online purchasing behaviour.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Online retailers has place much emphasis on customer trust aspect, trust is another way driving customer's behaviour in digital environment, which can depend on customer's attitude and expectation.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Indeed, the company's products design or ideas can not met customer's expectations.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Customer's purchase intention based on rational expectations, and additionally impacts on emotional trust.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Moreover, those expectations can be also establish on the product information and revision from others.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In several studies, perceived value, shopping style, and brand trust are the main factors that affect online consumers' decisions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The perceived value means that people can compare the products and prices online, bringing them the perceived value of getting more benefits online than in an offline store.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The comfortable environment that online shopping brings to customers can make consumers get more perceived value.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In the end, E-commerce behavior is still mostly influenced by families that are receptive to new technologies, and to a lesser extent by efficiency concerns.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Consumers find a product of interest by visiting the website of the retailer directly or by searching among alternative vendors using a shopping search engine.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Users can compare and evaluate products using product information on the website, as well on other websites such as websites about product tests.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Once a particular product has been found and selected on the website of the seller, most online retailers use shopping cart software to allow the consumer to accumulate multiple items and to adjust quantities, like filling a physical shopping cart or basket in a conventional store.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] A "checkout" process follows (continuing the physical-store analogy) in which payment and delivery information is collected, if necessary.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Some stores allow consumers to sign up for a permanent online account so that some or all of this information only needs to be entered once.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The consumer often receives an e-mail confirmation once the transaction is complete.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Less sophisticated stores may rely on consumers to phone or e-mail their orders (although full credit card numbers, expiry date, and Card Security Code, or bank account and routing number should not be accepted by e-mail, for reasons of security).
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] One of the great benefits of online shopping is the ability to read product reviews, written either by experts or fellow online shoppers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] According to the research, reviews on electronics (57%) such as DVD players, cellphones, or PlayStations, and so on, reviews on cars (45%), and reviews on software (37%) play an important role in influencing consumers who tend to make purchases online.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Furthermore, 40% of online shoppers indicate that they would not even buy electronics without consulting online reviews first.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Studies using eye-tracking can show how people pay attention to certain parts of reviews and product images, which can really show how and what they decide to get.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Other research shows that reviews that talk about certain prices, quality, and delivery tend to have a big impact on how customers tend to spend their money online.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In addition to online reviews, peer recommendations on online shopping pages or social media websites play a key role for online shoppers when they are researching future purchases.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] 90% of all purchases made are influenced by social media.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Online shoppers commonly use a credit card or a PayPal account in order to make payments.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Having a safe and reliable payment process can be a great way to build trust.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] If people feel their money is secure and safe within the buying process, they will most likely purchase the product and feel comfortable about it.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Some online shops will not accept international credit cards.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Some require both the purchaser's billing and shipping address to be in the same country as the online shop's base of operation.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Other online shops allow customers from any country to send gifts anywhere.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The financial part of a transaction may be processed in real time (e.g. letting the consumer know their credit card was declined before they log off), or may be done later as part of the fulfillment process.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Once a payment has been accepted, the goods or services can be delivered in the following ways.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Simple shopping cart systems allow the off-line administration of products and categories.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The shop is then generated as HTML files and graphics that can be uploaded to a webspace.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The systems do not use an online database.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] A high-end solution can be bought or rented as a stand-alone program or as an addition to an enterprise resource planning program.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] It is usually installed on the company's web server and may integrate into the existing supply chain so that ordering, payment, delivery, accounting and warehousing can be automated to a large extent.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Other solutions allow the user to register and create an online shop on a portal that hosts multiple shops simultaneously from one back office.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Examples are BigCommerce, Shopify and FlickRocket.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Open source shopping cart packages include advanced platforms such as Interchange, and off-the-shelf solutions such as Magento, osCommerce, WooCommerce, PrestaShop, and Zen Cart.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Commercial systems can also be tailored so the shop does not have to be created from scratch.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] By using an existing framework, software modules for various functionalities required by a web shop can be adapted and combined.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Customers are attracted to online shopping not only because of high levels of convenience, but also because of broader selections, competitive pricing, and greater access to information.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Business organizations seek to offer online shopping not only because it is of much lower cost compared to bricks and mortar stores, but also because it offers access to a worldwide market, increases customer value, and builds sustainable capabilities.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Designers of online shops are concerned with the effects of information load.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Information load is a product of the spatial and temporal arrangements of stimuli in the web store.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Compared with conventional retail shopping, the information environment of virtual shopping is enhanced by providing additional product information such as comparative products and services, as well as various alternatives and attributes of each alternative, etc.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Two major dimensions of information load are complexity and novelty.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Complexity refers to the number of different elements or features of a site, often the result of increased information diversity.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Novelty involves the unexpected, suppressed, new, or unfamiliar aspects of the site.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The novelty dimension may keep consumers exploring a shopping site, whereas the complexity dimension may induce impulse purchases.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Internet consumers are self-conscious and emphasize personalized consumption, which makes the demand for online consumption different.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Online consumers have different needs depending on their time and environment.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Even different online consumers have different needs at the same level of demand due to the difference in income level and other factors.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Compared with the centralized nature of traditional markets, online consumption is more decentralized.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In the online consumer market, consumers have a short decision time, a large variability of consumer demand, a large number of purchases, but a relatively small amount of each purchase, a considerable mobility of purchases, a strong substitutability of goods, and a large elasticity of demand.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] According to the output of a research report by Western Michigan University published in 2005, an e-commerce website does not have to be good looking with listing on a lot of search engines.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] It must build relationships with customers to make money.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The report also suggests that a website must leave a positive impression on the customers, giving them a reason to come back.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] How people tend to shop and how much they trust a company or brand are all very important factors that can either make or break whether a person buys online.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] If sites can give good product info, good visuals, and good, reliable reviews, they can make their online shoppers feel safer and overall persuade them to purchase something.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] However, resent research has proven that sites with higher focus on efficiency, convenience, and personalised services increased the customers motivation to make purchases.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] These concerns majorly affect the decisions of almost two thirds of the consumers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The most important factors determining whether customers return to a website are ease of use and the presence of user-friendly features.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Usability testing is important for finding problems and improvements in a web site.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Methods for evaluating usability include heuristic evaluation, cognitive walkthrough, and user testing.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Each technique has its own characteristics and emphasizes different aspects of the user experience.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The popularity of online shopping continues to erode sales of conventional retailers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] For example, Best Buy, the largest retailer of electronics in the U.S. in August 2014 reported its tenth consecutive quarterly dip in sales, citing an increasing shift by consumers to online shopping.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Amazon.com has the largest market share in the United States.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] As of May 2018, a survey found two-thirds of Americans had bought something from Amazon (92% of those who had bought anything online), with 40% of online shoppers buying something from Amazon at least once a month.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The survey found shopping began at amazon.com 44% of the time, compared to a general search engine at 33%.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] It estimated 75 million Americans subscribe to Amazon Prime and 35 million more use someone else's account.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] There were 242 million people shopping online in China in 2012.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] For developing countries and low-income households in developed countries, adoption of e-commerce in place of or in addition to conventional methods is limited by a lack of affordable Internet access.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Online stores are usually available 24 hours a day, and many consumers in Western countries have Internet access both at work and at home.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Other establishments such as Internet cafes, community centers and schools provide internet access as well.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In contrast, visiting a conventional retail store requires travel or commuting and costs such as gas, parking, or bus tickets, and must usually take place during business hours.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Delivery was always a problem which affected the convenience of online shopping.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Additionally, the online shopping industry has not only involved the concept of providing convenience for customers but also improved perceptions of social inclusion.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] However to overcome this many retailers including online retailers in Taiwan brought in a store pick up service.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] This now meant that customers could purchase goods online and pick them up at a nearby convenience store, making online shopping more advantageous to customers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In the event of a problem with the item (e.g., the product was not what the consumer ordered or the product was not satisfactory), consumers are concerned with the ease of returning an item in exchange for the correct product or a refund.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Consumers may need to contact the retailer, visit the post office and pay return shipping, and then wait for a replacement or refund.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Some online companies have more generous return policies to compensate for the traditional advantage of physical stores.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] For example, the online shoe retailer Zappos.com includes labels for free return shipping, and does not charge a restocking fee, even for returns which are not the result of merchant error.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] (Note: In the United Kingdom, online shops are prohibited from charging a restocking fee if the consumer cancels their order in accordance with the Consumer Protection (Distance Selling) Act 2000).
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] A 2018 survey in the United States found 26% of online shoppers said they never return items, and another 65% said they rarely do so.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Merchants may benefit from online shopping due to low sales inventory pressure, low operating costs, and the scale of operation is not limited by the site.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Especially in cases of large or heavy products, delivery can be not only more convenient but also not require having or using a car.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Online shopping is usually more informationally rich than shopping at physical stores traveled to and usually has higher comparability and customizability.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Some online stores provide or link to supplemental product information, such as instructions, safety procedures, demonstrations, or manufacturer specifications.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Research shows that when consumers are looking at reviews, they pay attention to both the text and the picture of the product.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Positive reviews and well-organized information can make people feel comfortable in themselves as a buyer and comfortable in the website or company they are shopping with.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Some provide background information, advice, or how-to guides designed to help consumers decide which product to buy.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Some stores even allow customers to comment or rate their items.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] There are also dedicated review sites that host user reviews for different products.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Reviews and even some blogs give customers the option of shopping for cheaper purchases from all over the world without having to depend on local retailers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In a conventional retail store, clerks are generally available to answer questions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Some online stores have real-time chat features, but most rely on e-mails or phone calls to handle customer questions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Even if an online store is open 24 hours a day, seven days a week, the customer service team may only be available during regular business hours.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] It also implies that geographical factors, rather than socioeconomic issues, must be addressed in order to improve online shopping acceptance.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] One advantage of shopping online is being able to quickly seek out deals for items or services provided by many different vendors (though some local search engines do exist to help consumers locate products for sale in nearby stores).
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Search engines, online price comparison services and discovery shopping engines can be used to look up sellers of a particular product or service.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Shipping costs (if applicable) reduce the price advantage of online merchandise, though depending on the jurisdiction, a lack of sales tax may compensate for this.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Shipping a small number of items, especially from another country, is much more expensive than making the larger shipments bricks-and-mortar retailers order.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Some retailers (especially those selling small, high-value items like electronics) offer free shipping on sufficiently large orders.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Another major advantage for retailers is the ability to rapidly switch suppliers and vendors without disrupting users' shopping experience.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Given the lack of ability to inspect merchandise before purchase, consumers are at higher risk of fraud than face-to-face transactions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] When ordering merchandise online, the item may not work properly, it may have defects, or it might not be the same item pictured in the online photo.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Merchants also risk fraudulent purchases if customers are using stolen credit cards or fraudulent repudiation of the online purchase.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] However, merchants face less risk from physical theft by using a warehouse instead of a retail storefront.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) encryption has generally solved the problem of credit card numbers being intercepted in transit between the consumer and the merchant.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] However, one must still trust the merchant (and employees) not to use the credit card information subsequently for their own purchases, and not to pass the information to others.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Also, hackers might break into a merchant's web site and steal names, addresses and credit card numbers, although the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard is intended to minimize the impact of such breaches.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Identity theft is still a concern for consumers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] A number of high-profile break-ins in the 2000s has prompted some U.S. states to require disclosure to consumers when this happens.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Computer security has thus become a major concern for merchants and e-commerce service providers, who deploy countermeasures such as firewalls and anti-virus software to protect their networks.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Phishing is another danger, where consumers are fooled into thinking they are dealing with a reputable retailer, when they have actually been manipulated into feeding private information to a system operated by a malicious party.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Denial of service attacks are a minor risk for merchants, as are server and network outages.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Quality seals can be placed on the Shop web page if it has undergone an independent assessment and meets all requirements of the company issuing the seal.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The purpose of these seals is to increase the confidence of online shoppers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] However, the existence of many different seals, or seals unfamiliar to consumers, may foil this effort to a certain extent.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] A number of resources offer advice on how consumers can protect themselves when using online retailer services.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Although the benefits of online shopping are considerable, when the process goes poorly it can create a thorny situation.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] A few problems that shoppers potentially face include identity theft, faulty products, and the accumulation of spyware.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] If users are required to put in their credit card information and billing/shipping address and the website is not secure, customer information can be accessible to anyone who knows how to obtain it.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Most large online corporations are inventing new ways to make fraud more difficult.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] However, criminals are constantly responding to these developments with new ways to manipulate the system.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Even though online retailers are making efforts to protect consumer information, it is a constant fight to maintain the lead.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] It is advisable to be aware of the most current technology and scams to protect consumer identity and finances.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Product delivery is also a main concern of online shopping.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Most companies offer shipping insurance in case the product is lost or damaged.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Some shipping companies will offer refunds or compensation for the damage, but this is up to their discretion.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Fencing is another growing societal problem associated with online platforms.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Stolen merchandise from brick and mortal retailers and cargo are easily resold to the public through third party marketplaces due to lack of accountability and regulation by online operators.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In the United States alone, businesses are facing the brunt of organized retail crime with the value of stolen goods amounting to $68.8 billion in 2021 (equivalent to 1.47% of all sales or $214 per capita nationwide).
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] These goods are typically passed off as legitimate, and resold online to unsuspecting buyers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The lack of full cost disclosure may also be problematic.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] While it may be easy to compare the base price of an item online, it may not be easy to see the total cost up front.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Additional fees such as shipping are often not visible until the final step in the checkout process.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] The problem is especially evident with cross-border purchases, where the cost indicated at the final checkout screen may not include additional fees that must be paid upon delivery such as duties and brokerage.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Some services such as the Canadian-based Wishabi attempts to include estimates of these additional cost, but nevertheless, the lack of general full cost disclosure remains a concern.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Privacy of personal information is a significant issue for some consumers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Many consumers wish to avoid spam and telemarketing which could result from supplying contact information to an online merchant.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] In response, many merchants promise to not use consumer information for these purposes, Many websites keep track of consumer shopping habits in order to suggest items and other websites to view.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Brick-and-mortar stores also collect consumer information.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Some ask for a shopper's address and phone number at checkout, though consumers may refuse to provide it.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] Many larger stores use the address information encoded on consumers' credit cards (often without their knowledge) to add them to a catalog mailing list.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] This information is obviously not accessible to the merchant when paying in cash or through a bank (money transfer, in which case there is also proof of payment).
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] High-volume websites, such as Yahoo!, Amazon.com and eBay offer hosting services for online stores to all size retailers.
[src:ecommerce-platform/online-shopping] These stores are presented within an integrated navigation framework, sometimes known as **virtual shopping malls** or online marketplaces.
[src:ecommerce-platform/sales-order] The **sales order**, sometimes abbreviated as **SO**, is an order issued by a business or sole trader to a customer.
[src:ecommerce-platform/sales-order] A sales order may be for products and/or services.
[src:ecommerce-platform/sales-order] Given the wide variety of businesses, this means that the orders can be fulfilled in several ways.
[src:ecommerce-platform/sales-order] A sales order is an internal document of the company, meaning it is generated by the company itself.
[src:ecommerce-platform/sales-order] A sales order should record the customer's originating purchase order which is an external document.
[src:ecommerce-platform/sales-order] Rather than using the customer's purchase order document, an internal sales order form allows the internal audit control of completeness to be monitored.
[src:ecommerce-platform/sales-order] A sequential sales order number may be used by the company for its sales order documents.
[src:ecommerce-platform/sales-order] The customer's PO is the originating document which triggers the creation of the sales order.
[src:ecommerce-platform/sales-order] A sales order, being an internal document, can therefore contain many customer purchase orders under it.
[src:ecommerce-platform/sales-order] In a manufacturing environment, a sales order can be converted into a work order to show that work is about to begin to manufacture, build or engineer the products the customer wants.
[src:ecommerce-platform/sales-order] Many sales orders are no longer paper-based, but rather transmitted electronically over a corporate Intranet.
[src:ecommerce-platform/sales-order] These sales orders may be communicated across different enterprise business applications.
[src:ecommerce-platform/sales-order] The automated sales and purchase order process enables customers to place orders 24/7, even when offices are closed.
[src:ecommerce-platform/sales-order] The steps involved in fulfilling the demands made in a sales order make up the order fulfillment process.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] A session is established at a certain point in time, and then ‘torn down’ - brought to an end - at some later point.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] An established communication session may involve more than one message in each direction.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] An established session is the basic requirement to perform a connection-oriented communication.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] A session also is the basic step to transmit in connectionless communication modes.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] However, any unidirectional transmission does not define a session.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] In the case of transport protocols that do not implement a formal session layer (e.g., UDP) or where sessions at the application layer are generally very short-lived (e.g., HTTP), sessions are maintained by a higher level program using a method defined in the data being exchanged.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] For example, an HTTP exchange between a browser and a remote host may include an HTTP cookie which identifies state, such as a unique session ID, information about the user's preferences or authorization level.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] HTTP/1.0 was thought to only allow a single request and response during one Web/HTTP Session.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Protocol version HTTP/1.1 improved this by completing the Common Gateway Interface (CGI), making it easier to maintain the Web Session and supporting HTTP cookies and file uploads.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Most client-server sessions are maintained by the transport layer - a single connection for a single session.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] However each transaction phase of a Web/HTTP session creates a separate connection.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Maintaining session continuity between phases requires a session ID.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] The session ID is embedded within the `<A HREF>` or `<FORM>` links of dynamic web pages so that it is passed back to the CGI.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] CGI then uses the session ID to ensure session continuity between transaction phases.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] One advantage of one connection-per-phase is that it works well over low bandwidth (modem) connections.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] TCP sessions are typically implemented in software using child processes and/or multithreading, where a new process or thread is created when the computer establishes or joins a session.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] HTTP sessions are typically not implemented using one thread per session, but by means of a database with information about the state of each session.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] The advantage with multiple processes or threads is relaxed complexity of the software, since each thread is an instance with its own history and encapsulated variables.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] The disadvantage is large overhead in terms of system resources, and that the session may be interrupted if the system is restarted.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] When a client may connect to any server in a cluster of servers, a special problem is encountered in maintaining consistency when the servers must maintain session state.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] The client must either be directed to the same server for the duration of the session, or the servers must transmit server-side session information via a shared file system or database.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Otherwise, the client may reconnect to a different server than the one it started the session with, which will cause problems when the new server does not have access to the stored state of the old one.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Server-side sessions are handy and efficient, but can become difficult to handle in conjunction with load-balancing/high-availability systems and are not usable at all in some embedded systems with no storage.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] The load-balancing problem can be solved by using shared storage or by applying forced peering between each client and a single server in the cluster, although this can compromise system efficiency and load distribution.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] A method of using server-side sessions in systems without mass-storage is to reserve a portion of RAM for storage of session data.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] This method is applicable for servers with a limited number of clients (e.g. router or access point with infrequent or disallowed access to more than one client at a time).
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Client-side sessions use cookies and cryptographic techniques to maintain state without storing as much data on the server.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] When presenting a dynamic web page, the server sends the current state data to the client (web browser) in the form of a cookie.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] The client saves the cookie in memory or on disk.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] With each successive request, the client sends the cookie back to the server, and the server uses the data to "remember" the state of the application for that specific client and generate an appropriate response.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] This mechanism may work well in some contexts; however, data stored on the client is vulnerable to tampering by the user or by software that has access to the client computer.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Data integrity: Nothing apart from the server should manipulate session data (accidentally or maliciously).
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Authenticity: Nothing apart from the server should be able to initiate valid sessions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] To accomplish this, the server needs to encrypt the session data before sending it to the client, and modification of such information by any other party should be prevented via cryptographic means.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Transmitting state back and forth with every request is only practical when the size of the cookie is small.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] In essence, client-side sessions trade server disk space for the extra bandwidth that each web request will require.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Moreover, web browsers limit the number and size of cookies that may be stored by a web site.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] To improve efficiency and allow for more session data, the server may compress the data before creating the cookie, decompressing it later when the cookie is returned by the client.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] A session token is a unique identifier that is generated and sent from a server to a client to identify the current interaction session.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] The client usually stores and sends the token as an HTTP cookie and/or sends it as a parameter in GET or POST queries.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] The reason to use session tokens is that the client only has to handle the identifier—all session data is stored on the server (usually in a database, to which the client does not have direct access) linked to that identifier.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Examples of the names that some programming languages use when naming their HTTP cookie include JSESSIONID (JSP), PHPSESSID (PHP), CGISESSID (CGI), and ASPSESSIONID (ASP).
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] In human–computer interaction, **session management** is the process of keeping track of a user's activity across sessions of interaction with the computer system.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Typical session management tasks in a desktop environment include keeping track of which applications are open and which documents each application has opened, so that the same state can be restored when the user logs out and logs in later.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] For a website, session management might involve requiring the user to re-login if the session has expired (i.e., a certain time limit has passed without user activity).
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] It is also used to store information on the server-side between HTTP requests.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] A desktop session manager is a program that can save and restore desktop sessions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] A desktop session is all the windows currently running and their current content.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Session management on Linux-based systems is provided by X session manager.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] On Microsoft Windows systems, session management is provided by the Session Manager Subsystem (smss.exe); user session functionality can be extended by third-party applications like twinsplay.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Session management is particularly useful in a web browser where a user can save all open pages and settings and restore them at a later date or on a different computer (see data portability).
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] To help recover from a system or application crash, pages and settings can also be restored on next run.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Internet Explorer, OmniWeb and Opera are examples of web browsers that support session management.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Session management is often managed through the application of cookies.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) is stateless.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Session management is the technique used by the web developer to make the stateless HTTP protocol support session state.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] For example, once a user has been authenticated to the web server, the user's next HTTP request (GET or POST) should not cause the web server to ask for the user's account and password again.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] In situations where multiple web servers must share knowledge of session state (as is typical in a cluster environment) session information must be shared between the cluster nodes that are running web server software.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] However, if session information is subject to audit compliance, consideration should be given to the method used for session storage, replication, and clustering.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] In a service-oriented architecture, Simple Object Access Protocol or SOAP messages constructed with Extensible Markup Language (XML) messages can be used by consumer applications to cause web servers to create sessions.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Just as HTTP is a stateless protocol, so is SMS.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] As SMS became interoperable across rival networks in 1999, and text messaging started its ascent towards becoming a ubiquitous global form of communication, various enterprises became interested in using the SMS channel for commercial purposes.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Initial services did not require session management since they were only one-way communications (for example, in 2000, the first mobile news service was delivered via SMS in Finland).
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] Today, these applications are referred to as application-to-peer (A2P) messaging as distinct from peer-to-peer (P2P) messaging.
[src:ecommerce-platform/session-computer-science] The development of interactive enterprise applications required session management, but because SMS is a stateless protocol as defined by the GSM standards, early implementations were controlled client-side by having the end-users enter commands and service identifiers manually.
